PROJECT: CNN Forward Layer GPU Implementation (Optimized)
=========================================================================
.. .. doxygenfile:: cnn_opencl.c
..    :project: CSE 160 - Introduction to Parallel Computing

Objective
---------


This is one of the project where you will be implementing and optimizing the forward pass of a convolution layer using OpenCL. Convolutional layers are the primary building blocks of convolutional neural networks (CNNs), which are used for tasks like image classification, object detection, natural language processing, and recommendation systems.

You will be working with a modified version of the LeNet5 architecture shown below:

.. image:: https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/84RlneM7JSDYDirUr_ceplL4G3-Peyq5dkLJTe2f-3Bj9KuWZjsH2A9Qq5PO5BRLrVfWGPnI3eQu8RkTPgyeUf9ZOWY9JbptVJy9LceAyHRn-O0kbzprx88yb82a5dnCR7EDP7n0

You can read about the original network:

*Source: http://yann.lecun.com/exdb/publis/pdf/lecun-01a.pdf*

.. image:: data:image/jpeg;base64,

*Source: https://rpubs.com/sunartorusli/cifar10*


Your optimized OpenCL implementation of the convolutional layer will be used to perform inference for layers C1 and C3 (shown in red) in the figure above.

This project is based on the paper "`Spatial Pyramid Pooling in Deep Convolutional Networks for Visual Recognition <https://arxiv.org/abs/1409.1556>`_" by He et al.

Input Data
----------

The network will be tested on the CIFAR-10 dataset, which contains 60,000 color images (32x32 pixels) across 10 different classes (airplane, automobile, bird, cat, deer, dog, frog, horse, ship, truck). Since the CIFAR-10 images are color images, you will have to deal with multiple channels (RGB) in your implementation. We will use a batch size of 1000 images for testing.

.. image:: data:image/jpeg;base64,

*Source: https://www.cs.toronto.edu/~kriz/cifar.html*

Instructions
------------
This project requires you to complete and fully optimize a GPU implementation of the convolutional layer. Performance of the GPU implementation is critical as this project aims to achieve maximum efficiency. The files you need to update to implement the forward convolution are:
``cnn_opencl.c`` and ``kernel.cl``. To understand which functions within these files are being called and when, it may be helpful to refer to ``cnn_seq.c``.

Again, you are performing the following operation:

.. code-block:: c

    for (int b = 0; b < B; b++) {                     // for each image in the batch 
        for (int m = 0; m < M; m++) {                 // for each output feature map
            for (int h = 0; h < H - K + 1; h++) {     // for each output element
                for (int w = 0; w < W - K + 1; w++) {
                    float sum = 0.0;
                    for (int c = 0; c < C; c++) {     // sum over all input feature maps
                        for (int p = 0; p < K; p++) { // KxK filter
                            for (int q = 0; q < K; q++) {
                                sum += input[((b * C + c) * H + (h + p)) * W + (w + q)] * kernel[((m * C + c) * K + p) * K + q];
                            }
                        }
                    }
                    output[((b * M + m) * (H - K + 1) + h) * (W - K + 1) + w] = sum;
                }
            }
        }
    }

This animation can help visualize this process better:

.. image:: https://stanford.edu/~shervine/teaching/cs-230/illustrations/convolution-layer-a.png?1c517e00cb8d709baf32fc3d39ebae67

*Source: https://stanford.edu/~shervine/teaching/cs-230/cheatsheet-convolutional-neural-networks#layer*

Beyond Convolution
------------------

In addition to the convolutional layers (C1 and C3), you are expected to implement the following:

1. **Activation Function (ReLU)**:
    - Apply the ReLU activation function to the output of the convolutional layers.
    - This can be implemented in the OpenCL kernel file `kernel.cl`.

2. **Pooling Layer (Max Pooling)**:
    - Implement the max pooling operation following the convolution and activation.
    - This helps in down-sampling the feature maps, reducing the dimensionality and computation.

3. **Fully Connected Layer** (Optional for extra credit):
    - Implement a fully connected layer using GPU.
    - Utilize local memory and tiled matrix multiplication for faster execution.
    - Be careful with matrix notation used in the codebase.

Optimization Tips
-----------------

1. **Use Local Memory**: Utilize local memory to cache frequently accessed data such as input tiles and filter weights.
2. **Tiling**: Divide the input and output into smaller tiles to better utilize the GPU's parallel processing capabilities.
3. **Coalesced Access**: Ensure memory accesses are coalesced to maximize memory bandwidth utilization.
4. **Loop Unrolling**: Unroll loops where possible to reduce loop overhead and increase instruction-level parallelism.
5. **Workgroup Size**: Experiment with different workgroup sizes to find the optimal configuration for your hardware.

How to Compile
--------------

The ``cnn_opencl.c`` and ``kernel.cl`` files contain the code for the programming project. Check the functions in the file for further guidance. There is a Makefile included which compiles it and links it with the necessary OpenCL libraries automatically. To compile and generate the executable:

For the sequential (CPU) version:

.. code-block:: sh

    make seq

For the OpenCL version with Intel OpenCL SDK:

.. code-block:: sh

    make intel

For the OpenCL version with NVIDIA OpenCL SDK:

.. code-block:: sh

    make nvidia

How to test
-----------

After compiling, you can run the program using the following commands:

For the sequential version:

.. code-block:: sh

    ./cnn_seq

For the OpenCL version (Intel):

.. code-block:: sh

    ./cnn_opencl

For the OpenCL version (NVIDIA):

.. code-block:: sh

    ./cnn_opencl

Test Output
-----------

The accuracy of your implementation should meet the baseline accuracy that our reference implementation achieves.

For the OpenCL version, you should see an output similar to the following:

.. code-block:: sh

    ❯ ./cnn_opencl 500 result.txt
    OpenCL_CNN      Images:  500
            Execution time: 0.042928 sec
            Image 0000: different confidence (1.000000 vs 0.954466)
            Accuracy: 0.904000

Extra credit
------------

For extra credit, you will implement a fully-connected layer using GPU. The arithmetic operation of a linear layer is equivalent to matrix multiplication. You should use local memory and tiled matrix multiplication for faster execution. Be careful with matrix notation used in the codebase.

The code for extra credit is also in ``cnn_opencl.c`` and ``kernel.cl``. Use ``make run-extra`` to test your program on a batch size of 1000 images; 
.. this is equivalent to executing ``make m2-extra`` and running ``./m2 1000``.
